abstract: The president addressed the Russia investigation, Roger Stone, the border wall, his dispute with the intelligence agencies and his competition in 2020.
snippet: The president addressed the Russia investigation, Roger Stone, the border wall, his dispute with the intelligence agencies and his competition in 2020.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump wanted to talk. He initially invited A. G. Sulzberger, the publisher of The New York Times, to an off-the-record dinner. Mr. Sulzberger countered with a request for an on-the-record interview that included Times reporters. The White House accepted.

abstract: President Trump indicated he will most likely take action on his own when the talks officially end in two weeks.
snippet: President Trump indicated he will most likely take action on his own when the talks officially end in two weeks.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A defiant President Trump declared on Thursday that he has all but given up on negotiating with Congress over his border wall and will build it on his own even as he dismissed any suggestions of wrongdoing in the investigations that have ensnared his associates.

abstract: The toughest progressive we’ve seen in a long time.
snippet: The toughest progressive we’ve seen in a long time.
lead_paragraph: The more you learn about Kamala Harris, the more formidable she appears. She is an amazing amalgam of different elements — highly educated elite meritocrat, Oakland street fighter, crusading, rough-elbow prosecutor, canny machine pol and telegenic rhetorical brawler.

abstract: Of obsessions, vanity and delusions of superiority.
snippet: Of obsessions, vanity and delusions of superiority.
lead_paragraph: Why is American politics so dysfunctional? Whatever the deeper roots of our distress, the proximate cause is ideological extremism: Powerful factions are committed to false views of the world, regardless of the evidence.

abstract: The 68-to-23 vote marks the second time in two months that a Republican-led Senate has admonished the president on foreign policy.
snippet: The 68-to-23 vote marks the second time in two months that a Republican-led Senate has admonished the president on foreign policy.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Senate, in a bipartisan rebuke to President Trump’s foreign policy, voted overwhelmingly to advance legislation drafted by the majority leader to express strong opposition to the president’s withdrawal of United States military forces from Syria and Afghanistan.

headline_main: What Happens Next for PG&E Executives?

abstract: The semantics are anything but trivial.
snippet: The semantics are anything but trivial.
lead_paragraph: Kellyanne Conway, White House adviser, recently dismissed as a “silly semantic argument” questions about President Trump’s use of the word “wall” — is it concrete, steel, see-through, a “smart wall,” slatted, piked, solar-powered, a chain-link fence or just a metaphor?
